               <note>
                  <ab type="description">Gorgora is a peninsula on the north of the <placeName
                        ref="LOC5888Tana">Lake Ṭana</placeName>. It is 12 km wide in its southern
                     part and stands on a strategical location, an elevated rocky promontory
                     overlooking the lake and next to a series of islands suitable for providing
                     shelter. The peninsula is located in today's <placeName ref="LOC1426Amhara"
                        >Amhara Regional State</placeName> while once formed part of the of the
                        <placeName ref="LOC2481Dambey">Dambǝyā</placeName> province. Gorgora gained
                     its prominence under the Jesuits as a missionary residence and a major Catholic
                     church thanks from a land grant offered by <roleName type="title">aṣe</roleName> <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos"
                        >Susǝnyos</persName> in 1607. In 1611, <persName ref="PRS9038Susenyos"
                        >Susǝnyos</persName> established a katamā in Gorgora and in 1621 he asked
                     the Jesuits to build a royal palace to the south-west, in an area that became
                     known as "New Gorgora". After the restauration of Orthodoxy, New Gorgora was
                     the first residence to be abandoned by the missionaries and, in 1665, <roleName type="title">aṣe</roleName>
                        <persName ref="PRS4015Fasilada">Fāsiladas</persName> ordered the burning of
                     the "books of Franks". The Italians seized the Gorgora peninsula on 14 April
                     1936 and in 1938 inaugurated ther on the Vetta Mussolin the Faro della
                     Conquista. </ab>
               </note>
